title: The Bourne Identity        (Jason Bourne, #1)
author: Ludlum, Robert
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I've only re-read two books in my life and this is one of them. It was one of the first non-school books I read that made me the reader I am today. ThI've only re-read two books in my life and this is one of them. It was one of the first non-school books I read that made me the reader I am today. The summer before my Senior year of high school (1989), we had a reading list that was just a bunch of authors (no specific books). I went to a Jesuit high school in CT. The list of authors included the likes of Clancy, Ludlum, Clavell, Cussler, Follet, etc. They were all pretty much books that you'd never read in class but that you may read for fun. The point was not to get you to read something, it was to get you to read ANYTHING. Anyway, my dad helped me pick out Ludlum and I got The Bourne Identity. Re-reading it now was a little different in that my tastes have evolved and matured. I still liked it but am guessing I didn't devour it or love it with the same gusto as before (which is why now I only give it 4 stars). Ludlum's long-time editor passed away in the early days of Covid. I wrote his widow a note of condolence and in it told her the story above and let her know her husband (and Ludlum) were responsible for my love of reading which has shaped me as a person. She wrote me back a thank you note. Funny, because of my dad's job we moved/lived in 3 states (TX, VA, CT) when I was in high school and the one in CT was my last one (I moved there the summer before my Senior year). Strange, Ludlum and his editor both lived in the town next to where I lived in CT. Had I not moved schools, I'm not certain I would have been the same reader/person I am today....more

It is Anthony Horowitz's take on James Bond right before and after becoming 007 officially. It was very fun and with a nice style to it. I've read one actual Ian Fleming Bond book and liked it but liked this one much better. It involves 007 going to Italy to investigate and revenge (if possible) his predecessor's murder. It involves some good creepy villains, a beautiful woman he partners with, Moneypenny, M, and lots of spy craft, espionage, mystery and elegance that has come to be known as Bond, James Bond. review: The story of a middle age man who used to be an author and is tagging along with his aging father (in his 80s) who is still practicing as a public defThe story of a middle age man who used to be an author and is tagging along with his aging father (in his 80s) who is still practicing as a public defender on his last case that involves adoptive, fundamentalist's parents accused of murder by abuse of their adoptee child from Ethiopia.I was tracking and liking the book up until the last 65 pages or so when it seemed to kind of take a sharp left turn heading into nowheresville (at least it seemed like rambling to me). This aimlessness may have been a literary technique consciously employed by the author but I'm not sure.Anyway, the crime and its retelling during the hearings were heartbreaking and disturbing. The father/son bonding was a little wooden but then again the father himself seemed like a odd duck but a very compassionate and unselfish one at that, like it was his job/lot in life to defend awful people knowing he'd lose 90% of the time and then pick-up all the pieces they leave behind and try to put them together which he did with the administrative emotion of working at the DMV yet always being totally committed to his stewardship and service of life after legal justice is meted out.Supposedly, this book could be semi-autobiographical given it's Guterson's first book in over a decade and his father was also a public defender. Unlike that prescriptive Beatles song regarding love, in the end of this book it's more rhetorical in asking if there is anything else other than it. In the end this may all be about Guterson himself both mourning and reconciling what his father meant both to him and the world around him....more

title: Five Decembers
author: Kestrel, James*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: A detective’s five-year journey switching back between two continents and a world war to investigate and ultimately avenge a three-time killer. Joe McA detective’s five-year journey switching back between two continents and a world war to investigate and ultimately avenge a three-time killer. Joe McGrady, an American veteran of Korea and Honolulu cop, is handed his first case, a grisly double-murder, to solve as an acting detective. Just weeks before the invasion of Pearl Harbor, McGrady begins to untangle the threads of the case and in doing so is propelled halfway around the world. Set-up, stranded and almost left for dead in a Hong Kong jail at the outbreak of the war, McGrady miraculously finds himself rescued but still sequestered behind enemy lines in Tokyo for the entire Second World War. Stuck in time and pining for the life and love he left behind, McGrady discovers key clues about one of the murder victims that begins to break the case open but also indelibly links him to its resolution. All the while, the captive American immerses himself in Japanese culture and finds new love with his pacifist, captor’s daughter. The war epic, wrapped within this murder mystery, climaxes during the night of the Tokyo firebombing after which McGrady returns like a ghost to a Hawaii that has changed forever and moved well past his assumed death. Restless to both resume and resolve the case as well as to keep his promise and repay the kindness of his captor, McGrady finally untangles the last knot of the mystery. In the end and after a lifetime to McGrady and a half-decade to everyone else, he surrenders to an ultimate peace after having been caught too many times in the middle of a world constantly at war with itself. Parts mystery, espionage, procedural, romance and war epic, Five Decembers is the best kind of pulp fiction noir with a protagonist the reader witnesses morph from common man to hardboiled and then morph again to at ease. The writing style echoes that of Chandler, Clavell and Hemingway while McGrady is an amalgamation of Travis McGee, Robert Jordan and everyone in between. At first blush, Five Decembers may seem anachronistic but once the last page is turned its timelessness is clear. ...more

title: The Twelve Lives of Alfred Hitchcock: An Anatomy of the Master of Suspense
author: White, Edward
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Part biography, part film s, part analysis of the man, his work and legacy, this is an interesting book that breaks Hitchcock down into twelve pPart biography, part film s, part analysis of the man, his work and legacy, this is an interesting book that breaks Hitchcock down into twelve personality aspects linked to his films by chapter such as “The Murderer”, “The Voyeur”, “The Womanizer”, “The Auteur”, etc.Lots of tidbits and keen observations peppered throughout such as, 1.) the death of his father coinciding with the zenith of Germany’s attacks on England during WWI and the 1918 influenza pandemic sweeping across Europe soon thereafter all of which seemed to shape his childhood, 2.) that had he not gotten into movies, he claims he would have been a criminal lawyer, 3.) that he was a worrier, incredibly vain, hugely insecure and constantly needing and getting reassurance from his wife, 4.) that both Graham Greene and Ernest Hemingway refused to work with him, 5.) he was Universal’s third largest shareholder at one point, 6.) he didn’t like Paul Newman because he didn’t wear a tie and drank beer (not wine) at one of his famed post shoot dinners, 7.) that Cézanne was his favorite artist.Certainly, a true original and yet, like many brilliant, creative icons, very much a creepy weirdo. That aside (if you can separate the man from his work), his movies and his influence remain both indelibly etched in our modern culture and presciently relevant more than 50 years after his death.The book was a fun read and I like the various film interpretations the best....more

title: A Tale for the Time Being
author: Ozeki, Ruth*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: An interesting book all around. From the title of the book, to the main character's name and the overall message, this was certainly a "thought-provokAn interesting book all around. From the title of the book, to the main character's name and the overall message, this was certainly a "thought-provoking" book :-). Early on, the main character, Nao, reminded me a lot of Holden Caulfield but over the course of the book she matured beyond her years. The author did a very nice job peeling the onion back on her cast of characters and in unfolding their respective truths creating a shared understanding amongst all. The technique of telling the story across a continuum of time that switched back and forth and then became intertwined kept the pace moving and the mystery of the story fresh till the end.In the end, I think this book is a parable (aka "a tale") for the living (aka "the time being") to live in the now and do your best knowing that life is a journey with many bends in the road and that wisdom and knowledge come as time passes and experience is gained and that patience and understanding are required along the way to acquire both. And I think telling the story from the perspective of a teenager reminds adults at just how imperfect and fragile we are as humans (even though we may have tricked ourselves as being the smartest people in the room). Ah, if I only knew then (when I was sixteen) what I know now (at 49)...which is another way of saying in another 33 years, if I only knew then (when I was 49) what I know now (at 82). As Bob Dylan sings in My Back Pages, "Ah, but I was so much older then, I'm younger than that now."...more

review: This book is mostly about the history and science behind the topic of extinction and how we (humans) are creating the next extinction and our own demiThis book is mostly about the history and science behind the topic of extinction and how we (humans) are creating the next extinction and our own demise. It won the Pulitzer Prize. I've never really been into science and unfortunately this book didn't convert me. It's not that I don't believe in science (I do), it just doesn't hold my interest. The more I read King (as I'm older) I think more about what he's saying. In this case, this books almost seems like his salute to post 9-11 vets and the battles they've waged both on and off duty. Billy is a complex character. Killing for $ but only bad guys and doesn't really seem to care all that much about the $. Just pretty much on a mission to rid the world of bad people as if that's his life purpose and one he came to at an early age and then honed in Iraq.
